---
/**
 * "VQE — the variational hybrid loop" — Phase 6 closing essay.
 *
 * This is the final essay in the v3 reading path. It composes the
 * Phase 6 building blocks into one two-half essay:
 *
 *   - Algorithm half (ALG-08):
 *     1. Hook — the quantum computer tries a wavefunction; the
 *        classical computer turns the knobs (D-29).
 *     2. Static `CircuitView` of the 2-parameter
 *        `Ry(θ₁) ⊗ Ry(θ₂) → CNOT(0,1)` ansatz, built at
 *        frontmatter time from `DEFAULT_INITIAL_THETAS` so the
 *        snapshot matches the EnergyLandscape's default marker
 *        position (D-18). The existing baked "Copy as Qiskit"
 *        button on CircuitView gives the reader a portable
 *        starting point.
 *     3. Slim VQE-local `<p data-role="ansatz-readout">` mirror
 *        that listens for the `vqe:thetachange` CustomEvent
 *        dispatched by EnergyLandscape's hydrator and updates the
 *        live `(θ₁, θ₂)` text as the reader drags / Auto-descends
 *        the marker (D-19). No global CircuitView mutation.
 *     4. `<EnergyLandscape />` embed.
 *     5. Hand-off paragraph — energy minimization is the
 *        conceptual bridge (D-29).
 *
 *   - Use-case half (USE-05):
 *     1. Near-term industrial framing with explicit reality check
 *        and primary-source citations (D-27, D-30). Every
 *        quantitative or roadmap claim links to its source.
 *     2. `<MoleculeGallery />` embed.
 *     3. Reality check paragraph — what VQE on near-term hardware
 *        can and cannot do today (D-30).
 *     4. Qiskit CTA — the gallery's Copy buttons let you go run a
 *        real ansatz in Qiskit.
 *
 *   - Self-test + `MathNerds` appendix covering the expectation-
 *     value energy functional, the central finite-difference
 *     gradient, and the GD-with-momentum update rule.
 *
 *   - Footer-nav: prev /shor, next /sandbox.
 *
 * Convention: qubit register is `|q1 q0⟩` (Qiskit / LSB-first).
 * The ansatz Circuit literal here, the sandbox starter in
 * `tests/essays/sandbox-links.test.ts`, and the H₂ entry in
 * `src/data/molecules.json` all share the same op shape so the
 * static snapshot, the live landscape, the gallery, and the
 * sandbox round-trip a single source of truth.
 *
 * D-18, D-19, D-27..D-30, D-43, D-44, D-45.
 */
import EssayLayout from "../layouts/EssayLayout.astro";
import MathBlock from "../components/MathBlock.astro";
import MathNerds from "../components/MathNerds.astro";
import CircuitView from "../components/CircuitView.astro";
import EnergyLandscape from "../components/EnergyLandscape.astro";
import MoleculeGallery from "../components/MoleculeGallery.astro";
import {
  DEFAULT_INITIAL_THETAS,
  rotOp,
  cnotOp,
  type Circuit,
} from "../lib/quantum";

const [theta1Seed, theta2Seed] = DEFAULT_INITIAL_THETAS;

// Same op shape as `src/data/molecules.json` H₂ entry and the
// `vqe` sandbox starter so the static snapshot, the gallery card,
// and the sandbox-link round-trip one canonical ansatz.
const ansatzCircuit: Circuit = {
  qubits: 2,
  steps: [
    [rotOp("Y", 0, theta1Seed)],
    [rotOp("Y", 1, theta2Seed)],
    [cnotOp(0, 1)],
  ],
};

const fmt = (n: number) => n.toFixed(3);
---

<EssayLayout
  title="VQE — the variational hybrid loop"
  subtitle="Shor needs a fault-tolerant machine that doesn't exist yet. The variational quantum eigensolver — VQE — is the credible near-term direction: a small parameterised circuit on the quantum side, a classical optimizer on the other, and the two passing energy back and forth until the parameters settle into a minimum. Same loop drives small-molecule chemistry, materials, and the rest of the variational/hybrid family."
  description="Walk through the VQE hybrid loop: a 2-parameter Ry⊗Ry→CNOT ansatz, an H₂ energy landscape you can drag and auto-descend, and a gallery of pre-baked VQE results for H₂, HeH⁺, and LiH. Honest scope — small benchmark molecules on noisy near-term hardware, with classical baselines like HF / CCSD still hard competition. Sourced. Covers ALG-08 and USE-05."
>
  <p>
    The <a href="/shor">previous essay</a> ended with a hard
    boundary: Shor is exponentially fast on a quantum computer, and
    that quantum computer doesn't exist yet at any cryptographically
    relevant scale. The fault-tolerant logical-qubit counts the RSA
    widget surveyed are years to decades away under every published
    roadmap. So what runs on the noisy 50–500-qubit machines we
    actually have today?
  </p>

  <p>
    The honest answer is "variational" / "hybrid" algorithms — a
    family whose flagship is <strong>VQE</strong>, the variational
    quantum eigensolver. VQE doesn't need a fault-tolerant machine.
    It runs a small parameterised circuit on the quantum side,
    measures an expected energy, hands that scalar to a classical
    optimizer, and lets the optimizer turn the circuit's parameters
    until the energy stops going down. Small benchmark molecules
    fit. Real industrial chemistry is active research. Classical
    baselines like Hartree–Fock (HF) and coupled cluster (CCSD)
    remain hard competition. The story this essay tells is the loop
    and the framing — neither one tries to claim quantum has
    already won.
  </p>

  <h2>The hook: the quantum computer tries a wavefunction; the classical computer turns the knobs</h2>

  <p data-step="0">
    The conceptual loop is two parts:
  </p>

  <ol class="my-4 list-decimal space-y-2 pl-6 text-ink">
    <li>
      A <em>parameterised quantum circuit</em> takes a list of real
      knobs <code>θ = (θ₁, θ₂, …)</code> and prepares a candidate
      wavefunction <code>|ψ(θ)⟩</code>. Run it on real hardware (or
      a simulator), measure the energy
      <code>E(θ) = ⟨ψ(θ)| Ĥ |ψ(θ)⟩</code> for the problem
      Hamiltonian <code>Ĥ</code> you care about.
    </li>
    <li>
      A <em>classical optimizer</em> reads <code>E(θ)</code> and
      proposes a better <code>θ</code>. Gradient descent works if
      the surface is smooth enough; for noisy hardware people use
      gradient-free methods (COBYLA, SPSA) too. Either way the
      classical side never touches the qubits — it just turns the
      knobs and asks for another energy.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    The two halves of this essay walk the loop. The algorithm half
    builds the smallest non-trivial VQE setup: a 2-parameter ansatz
    and a documented 2D energy surface that's actually H₂ in a
    minimal basis. The use-case half points the same loop at a
    gallery of pre-baked molecule results and frames where this
    matters and where it still doesn't.
  </p>

  <h2>The parameterised ansatz</h2>

  <p data-step="1">
    The "ansatz" is the parameterised circuit family the optimizer
    is allowed to search inside. For the canonical 2-qubit H₂ demo,
    the simplest hardware-efficient ansatz is one
    <code>Ry</code> rotation per qubit followed by a single
    <code>CNOT</code> to entangle them. Two real parameters
    <code>(θ₁, θ₂)</code> in, one entangled 2-qubit state out:
  </p>

  <CircuitView
    circuit={ansatzCircuit}
    caption={`Hardware-efficient 2-qubit VQE ansatz: Ry(θ₁) on q₀, Ry(θ₁ → θ₂) on q₁, then CNOT(q₀ → q₁). Shown at the default seed (θ₁ = ${fmt(theta1Seed)}, θ₂ = ${fmt(theta2Seed)}); Copy as Qiskit emits Python you can paste straight into a notebook.`}
  />

  <p data-step="2">
    The Copy-as-Qiskit button bakes the ansatz into a portable
    Qiskit snippet — same ansatz as the H₂ card in the gallery
    below, same starter as the <code>vqe</code> sandbox link.
    That's the artifact you'd plug into a real
    <code>VQE</code> driver to estimate ground-state energies for
    a Hamiltonian <em>you</em> supply.
  </p>

  <h2>The energy landscape</h2>

  <p data-step="3">
    For our pedagogical H₂ surface the energy depends only on
    <code>(θ₁, θ₂)</code>, so the whole optimization problem fits
    on a 2D map. The widget below renders that surface as a 50×50
    heatmap with contour bands; drag the marker (or press
    <strong>Auto-descend</strong>) to walk gradient descent
    downhill from any starting point you pick. <strong>Reseed</strong>
    cycles through six deterministic starts so you can feel that
    every seed in the basin lands on the same minimum at
    <code>(π, π)</code>.
  </p>

  <p
    data-role="ansatz-readout"
    aria-live="polite"
    class="my-3 rounded-md border border-line bg-surface-elevated/40 px-4 py-2 font-mono text-sm text-ink-emphasis tabular-nums"
  >
    Live ansatz parameters: θ₁ = <span data-field="theta1">{fmt(theta1Seed)}</span>, θ₂ = <span data-field="theta2">{fmt(theta2Seed)}</span>
  </p>

  <EnergyLandscape
    caption="H₂ energy surface E(θ₁, θ₂) over [0, 2π]². Cool indigo cells are low energy (the basin); warm amber is high. The cross-hair marks the documented minimum at (π, π). Drag the marker or press Auto-descend to walk the same gradient-descent trajectory the tests pin to within 1e-3 of the true minimum."
  />

  <p data-step="4">
    That is the conceptual bridge to the second half of the essay:
    <em>energy minimization is the loop</em>. The optimizer doesn't
    know about chemistry, basis sets, or qubits — it just sees a
    scalar function <code>E(θ)</code> and walks downhill. Whatever
    chemistry (or materials, or combinatorial-optimization)
    problem you encode in the Hamiltonian, the same loop runs.
  </p>

  <h2>What this loop is for: small-molecule chemistry</h2>

  <p data-step="5">
    The flagship near-term application is quantum chemistry — and
    specifically the ground-state energy of small molecules. The
    earliest VQE paper estimated the ground state of HeH⁺ on a
    six-photon photonic device
    (<a href="https://doi.org/10.1038/ncomms5213" rel="noopener external">Peruzzo et al.,
    <em>Nature Communications</em> 5, 4213 (2014)</a>). IBM's
    hardware-efficient ansatz extension covered H₂, LiH, and BeH₂
    on superconducting hardware
    (<a href="https://doi.org/10.1038/nature23879" rel="noopener external">Kandala et al.,
    <em>Nature</em> 549, 242 (2017)</a>). The current state of the
    field and the open scaling questions are surveyed by
    <a href="https://doi.org/10.1021/acs.chemrev.8b00803" rel="noopener external">Cao et al.,
    <em>Chemical Reviews</em> 119, 10856 (2019)</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    The gallery below pre-bakes converged VQE results for three
    small molecules at equilibrium bond distance. Each card shows
    the ansatz parameters the classical optimizer settled on, the
    converged energy in both Hartree and electron-volts, and a
    Copy-as-Qiskit button against the data-derived ansatz circuit
    — same engine you just felt in the landscape, pointed at three
    different Hamiltonians.
  </p>

  <MoleculeGallery
    caption="Pre-baked VQE results for H₂, HeH⁺, and LiH at equilibrium bond distance. The bond-distance slider on each card is illustrative — energies are not re-computed live (D-25). Sources are cited inline on every card."
  />

  <p data-step="6">
    What this loop is <em>not</em>, today: a drop-in replacement
    for classical quantum-chemistry pipelines. The molecules in
    the gallery are textbook benchmarks. Real industrial systems
    have hundreds of correlated electrons; even with active-space
    reductions, the qubit and gate counts are well past what
    near-term hardware can run to chemical accuracy. Classical
    baselines like Hartree–Fock and coupled-cluster (especially
    CCSD(T) — the "gold standard" for small molecules) remain
    hard competition; demonstrating quantum advantage on a real
    chemistry workload is active research, not a settled result.
    Noise and barren-plateau training pathologies are the two
    open problems papers keep returning to.
  </p>

  <p>
    What variational/hybrid methods <em>do</em> give you, today,
    is a credible near-term direction. You've built the loop in
    the browser — the same loop people are running on superconducting
    and trapped-ion hardware right now. The gallery's Copy buttons
    let you go from this page straight to a Qiskit notebook and
    run a real ansatz against the H₂ Hamiltonian. From there,
    swapping in your own Hamiltonian is one more step.
  </p>

  <h2>Self-test</h2>

  <ol class="my-6 list-decimal space-y-3 pl-6 text-ink">
    <li>
      In the EnergyLandscape widget, press <strong>Reseed</strong>
      until you land on a seed in the upper-left of the surface
      (e.g. small <code>θ₁</code> and small <code>θ₂</code>). Press
      <strong>Auto-descend</strong>. The trajectory still ends at
      <code>(π, π)</code>. Why is the minimum at <em>that</em>
      point and not somewhere else? (Hint: open the math appendix
      and look at the form of <code>h2Energy(θ₁, θ₂)</code> — it's
      a separable sum of two cosines.)
    </li>
    <li>
      The gallery's bond-distance slider is disabled. If you were
      actually allowed to drag it for the H₂ card, which step of
      the VQE loop would have to re-run for the energy readout to
      stay honest? (Answer: the Hamiltonian itself changes with
      bond distance — re-encoding <code>Ĥ</code> and re-running
      the entire variational loop is what an interactive slider
      would have to do. Pre-baking only the equilibrium result is
      why the slider is illustrative.)
    </li>
  </ol>

  <MathNerds title="The energy functional, the gradient, and the update rule">
    <p>
      VQE is variational because it minimizes an expectation
      value. For a problem Hamiltonian <code>Ĥ</code> and a
      parameterised state <code>|ψ(θ)⟩</code>, the cost is the
      expected energy:
    </p>
    <MathBlock tex="E(\theta) \;=\; \langle \psi(\theta) \,|\, \hat H \,|\, \psi(\theta) \rangle" />
    <p>
      The Rayleigh–Ritz variational principle says
      <code>E(θ) ≥ E₀</code> for all <code>θ</code>, with
      equality only when <code>|ψ(θ)⟩</code> is the true ground
      state. Minimizing <code>E(θ)</code> over the ansatz family
      is therefore a principled lower bound on the true ground
      energy — never below it, never <em>about</em> something
      else.
    </p>
    <p>
      The optimizer needs a gradient, and on noisy hardware the
      easiest gradient is the central finite difference (FD). For
      each parameter <code>θᵢ</code>, perturb up and down by a
      small <code>ε</code> and take the central difference:
    </p>
    <MathBlock tex="\frac{\partial E}{\partial \theta_i} \;\approx\; \frac{E(\theta + \varepsilon\, e_i) \,-\, E(\theta - \varepsilon\, e_i)}{2\varepsilon}" />
    <p>
      One pair of energy evaluations per parameter. (Real VQE
      implementations often use the parameter-shift rule with
      <code>ε = π/2</code> instead, which gives exact gradients
      on standard rotation gates and avoids the finite-difference
      bias — same shape, different shift.)
    </p>
    <p>
      With a gradient in hand, the optimizer used by this essay's
      Auto-descend is plain gradient descent with momentum:
    </p>
    <MathBlock tex="v_{k+1} \;=\; \mu\, v_k \,-\, \eta\, \nabla E(\theta_k); \qquad \theta_{k+1} \;=\; \theta_k \,+\, v_{k+1}" />
    <p>
      where <code>η</code> is the learning rate and
      <code>μ ∈ [0, 1)</code> is the momentum coefficient. The
      exact <code>(η, μ)</code> and convergence tolerance the
      site ships are pinned in
      <code>src/lib/quantum/vqe.ts</code> and verified by
      <code>tests/quantum/vqe.test.ts</code> against the true
      minimum to <code>1e-3</code>. The Auto-descend animation
      replays the same trajectory those tests certify.
    </p>
  </MathNerds>

  <Fragment slot="footer-nav">
    <a href="/shor" class="hover:text-ink">← Shor + post-quantum</a>
    <a href="/sandbox" class="hover:text-ink">Next: open the Sandbox →</a>
  </Fragment>
</EssayLayout>

<script>
  import { attachScrolly } from "../lib/scrolly";
  import { mountAnnotations } from "../lib/annotations";

  const root = document.querySelector("article");
  if (root) {
    attachScrolly(root, {
      stepSelector: "[data-step]",
      onStep: (i) => console.debug(`[scrolly] step ${i}`),
    });
  }

  const ann = mountAnnotations();
  document.getElementById("reset-annotations")?.addEventListener("click", () => {
    ann.reset();
  });

  // VQE-local live readout (D-19). Listens for the
  // `vqe:thetachange` CustomEvent dispatched by
  // `EnergyLandscape`'s hydrator and mirrors the current
  // (θ₁, θ₂) into the slim `<p data-role="ansatz-readout">`
  // block above the landscape. Stays VQE-local so we don't
  // overload CircuitView with animated labels.
  const readout = document.querySelector<HTMLElement>(
    '[data-role="ansatz-readout"]',
  );
  if (readout) {
    const t1Field = readout.querySelector<HTMLElement>('[data-field="theta1"]');
    const t2Field = readout.querySelector<HTMLElement>('[data-field="theta2"]');
    document.addEventListener("vqe:thetachange", (ev: Event) => {
      const detail = (ev as CustomEvent<{ theta1: number; theta2: number }>)
        .detail;
      if (!detail) return;
      if (t1Field) t1Field.textContent = detail.theta1.toFixed(3);
      if (t2Field) t2Field.textContent = detail.theta2.toFixed(3);
    });
  }
</script>
